description:
NUMBER: 20210517
SPECIES: Northern Periodical Cicada, Magicicada septendecim Linnaeus, 1758[1]
OTHER NAMES: 17-year cicada, Linnaeus’ periodical cicada, pharaoh cicada
DISTINCTIONS: Largest, most northern, and most famous 17-year cicada in USA.  Male posterior triangular with rounded tip not projected in peduncle.  Body black, eyes red, wings clear.  Distinct orange bands on bottom (ventral) of thorax, and orange at insertion of wings behind the eyes.
BROOD: X (1749 cicadas emerging in NEUSA, Marlatt, 1923)
DATE: 17 May 2021
LOCALITY: Falls Church, Virginia 22042
LATITUDE, LONGITUDE: 38.8690, -77.1680
DISTRIBUTION: The Brood X (10) emergence outbreak is supposed to be occurring throughout Washington DC, southcentral through southeast Pennsylvania, extreme northern Maryland and Virginia, and northeast arm of West Virginia, USA.  The locality we report is just in the southern edge of the predicted region.
DAMAGE: They usually cause little physical damage to plants.  Their loud calls can be irritating particularly in mass.  They do not bite or sting.
USES: Spectacular emergencies of billions attract attention.  Eatable by humans.  Fed on by practicably everything but last too briefly to be of much importance.
SIMILAR SPECIES: Cassin’s 17-year Cicada, Magicicada cassinii (Fisher, 1852), differs by having all-black beneath the thorax instead of black with distinct orange bands, and orange instead of brown legs.  Decula 17-year Cicada, Magicicada septendecula Alexander and Moore, 1962, is smaller and rare.  It similarly has well-defined orange stripes on the underside of the abdomen but no orange coloration in front of the wing insertion behind the eye.  Riley’s 13-year Cicada, Magicicada tredecim (Walsh and Riley, 1868), is light orange to caramel on the underside of the thorax and abdomen.
COMMENT: The Alexander and Moore (1962) name M. septendecula is unfortunately very confusing in similarity.
IMPORTANCE: This is the year for mass emergence of Brood X cicadas.  Thus of use to report where and when outbreaks occur.
OBSERVERS: Dr. Ernest H. Williams, Jr.[2,3,5,6] and Dr. Lucy Bunkley-Williams[2,4,5,7]
AFILIATIONS, ADDRESSES: [2]Extraordinary Professors, Potchefstroom Campus, North-West University, South Africa; Adjunct Professors, Research Field Station, Florida Gulf Coast University, 5164 Bonita Beach Road, Bonita Springs, FL 34134; [3]Dept. Marine Sciences, University of Puerto Rico (retired); [4]Dept. Biology, UPR (retired); [5]920 St. Andrews Blvd, Naples, FL 34113-8943; [6]e-mail ermest.williams1@upr.edu; cell 239-227-3645, ORCID 0000-0003-0913-3013; [7]Cell 787-467-2179, e-mail lucy.williams1@upr.edu, ORCID 0000-0003-1390-911x.
REFERENCES:
<>Alexander, R. D. and T. M. Moore. 1962. The evolutionary relationships of 17-year and 13-year cicadas, and three new species (Homoptera, Cicadidae, Magicicada). Miscellaneous Publications, Museum of Zoology, University of Michigan, No. 121: 59 pp. https://orthsoc.org/sina/c700lam62.pdf
<>Marlatt, C. L. 1923. The periodic cicada. U. S. Department of Agriculture, Bureau of Entomology, Bulletin 71: 183 pp., 68 figs., 6 plates. https://archive.org/details/periodicalcicad00marlgoog/page/n13/mode/2up
<>Williams, E. H., Jr.  and L. Bunkley-Williams. 2021. A record of a mass emergence in the North Periodical Cicada, Magicicada septendecim Linnaeus, in the Brood X outbreak. Research Quality Report, iNaturalist #82910494, 13 June (open access) [568]
ADDITIONAL FOOTNOTE:
[1]Identification was peer-reviewed, text edited and condensed.  The entire, original text is available in our reprint 568.

description: Black-eyed cicada

Brood X is highly local in occurence.  They emerged in Princeton this week.  Not finding them in Somerset.  YET. 

The last emergence (17 years ago?) also skipped Somerset.  It would be interesting to know where else they are being heard. 

 
Is 2021 a cicada year in New Jersey?

The answer to that question is yes. 

After 17 years in the ground, the Brood X cicada has emerged in New Jersey. 

Periodical cicadas are grouped into geographic broods based on the calendar year they emerge. In 1898, an entomologist identified 30 different broods, 17 with a 17-year life cycle and 13 with a 13-year life cycle, all of which have a Roman numeral assigned to them. 

Only 15 broods are known to have survived today, including the Brood X.

Now that the Brood X has graced the Garden State with its presence, here are answers to the questions everyone is asking.

Seth Ausubel, who was visiting Princeton, NJ, from New York City, spotted cicadas on Tuesday, May 25, 2021. He submitted the photo to Cicada Safari.
Are cicadas in New Jersey?
Yes. Cicadas have come by the thousands to the following locations in New Jersey, according to Cicada Safari, a mobile app that allows users to track cicadas they see.
THE FOLLOWING LOCATIONS HAVE CICADAS THIS WEEK
Princeton area of Mercer County
Hopewell in Mercer
Clinton
Kingwood
Lambertville

Still somewhat teneral, showing the variation in appearance of the tergite margins depending on the position of the abdomen.

This is a problematic cicada! Though clearly cassinii (that's all that has emerged in my location), it has an aberrant orange patch behind its right eye. The patch extends onto the pleura, and (interestingly) there is an orange patch on the right side of the head as well, between the eye and the cibarium (photo 5). This casts a little doubt on septendecim IDs made exclusively based on the presence of thoracic patches, and reinforces the importance of side + underside shots for ID.

I'll be interested to see if I encounter any more like this one; it may be a rare aberration.

NUMBER: 20210517
SPECIES: Northern Periodical Cicada, Magicicada septendecim Linnaeus, 1758
OTHER NAMES: 17-year cicada, Linnaeus’ periodical cicada, pharaoh cicada
DISTINCTIONS: Largest, most northern, and most famous 17-year cicada in USA.  Male posterior triangular with rounded tip not projected in peduncle.  Body black, eyes red, wings clear.
SPECIMENS: 4 adults and 3 attached tests from last (5th) molt.  Two on far right are female (left) and male (right).
BROOD: X (1749 cicadas emerging in NEUSA, Marlatt, 1923)
DATE: 17 May 2021
LOCALITY: Falls Church, Virginia 22042
LATITUDE, LONGITUDE: 38.8690, -77.1680
DISTRIBUTION: The Brood X (10) emergence outbreak is supposed to be occurring throughout Washington DC, southcentral through southeast Pennsylvania, extreme northern Maryland and Virginia, and northeast arm of West Virginia, USA.  The locality we report is just in the southern edge of the predicted region.
DAMAGE: They usually cause little physical damage to plants.  Their loud calls can be irritating particularly in mass.  They do not bite or sting.
USES: Spectacular emergencies of billions attract attention.  Eatable by humans.  Fed on by practicably everything but last too briefly to be of much importance.
SIMILAR SPECIES: Four species share the 17-year emergence spacing.
COMMENT: The Alexander and Moore (1962) name M. septendecula is unfortunately very confusing.
IMPORTANCE: This is the year for mass emergence of Brood X cicadas.  Thus of use to report where and when outbreaks occur.
OBSERVERS: Dr. Ernest H. Williams, Jr.[2,3,5,6] and Dr. Lucy Bunkley-Williams[2,4,5,7]

The only location I could find having any Magicicada species west of I-65 in Louisville.   I checked Central Park, Old Louisville neighborhood,  The Belknap campus of the University of Louisville where there are many very old trees and even a wooded patch, and Shawnee Park in northwestern Louisville.  Did not find any speciments dead or alive and could not hear any chorusing. 

What was unusual about Iroquois Park is that Magicicada chorusing could only be heard in the southwestern section of this 150 year old 750 acre Park.  No calls on the eastern or northern section at all.  Passersby confirmed that had been the case for the whole month.  Strange.

description:
It would be interesting to see cicadas Brood X evolution tree. They are truly bezoar insects. They have 5 eyes to navigate the above ground world. 2 compound eyes and 3 ocellus. The term "ocellus" (plural ocelli) is derived from the Latin world oculus (eye), and literally means "little eye".

I'm assuming their eyes are very similar to Australian ‘Redeye’ cicada-Psaltoda moerens eyes. The Research School of Biology at Australian National University did a study in 2015 and discovered in the red eye cicada 8 retinular cells form a fused rhabdom. They noted in particular that cicadas are the only Hemipteran group with fused rhabdoms, thus making Hemiptera an interesting case to study the evolution of open rhabdoms and neural superposition. 

The compound eyes have large visual fields, about 7500 ommatidia per eye. These tube like Structures remind me of the spore surface of polypore mushrooms. That black spot in their eyes that appears to be always looking at you is really you looking down the structured like tubes of their ommatidia. They have binocular overlaps of 10-15° in the frontal and of 50-60° in the dorsal visual field. The diameters of corneal facet lenses range between 22 and 34 μm and the lenses are unusually long with up to 100 μm in some eye regions. In the posterior part of the eyes, the hexagonal facet array changes to a square lattice. The compound eyes are of the eucone apposition type with 8 retinular cells contributing to a fused rhabdom in each ommatidium. The red eye colour is due to the pigment granules in the secondary pigment cells. They found a small Dorsal Rim Area (DRA), in which rhabdom cross-sections are rectangular rather than round. The cross-sections of DRA rhabdoms do not systematically change orientation along the length of the rhabdom, indicating that microvilli directions do not twist, which would make retinular cells in the DRA polarization sensitive.

The three ocelli have unusual lenses with a champagne-cork shape in longitudinal sections. Retinular cells are short in the dorsal and ventral part of the retinae, and long in their equatorial part. Ocellar rhabdoms are short (<10 μm), positioned close to the corneagenous layer and are formed by pairs of retinular cells. In cross-section, the rhabdomeres are 2-5 μm long and straight. The red color of ocelli is produced by screening pigments that form an iris around the base of the ocellar lens and by screening pigments between the ocellar retinular cells.

Information from 
https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26335848/

https://www.biology-pages.info/C/CompoundEye.html

description: Found energetically walking up the driveway, still alive and active.

I noticed that the ash leaves were falling in large quantities in our yard, and found that almost all of the stems had oviposition scars. This is a dissected leaf stem, showing the egg nests corresponding to each slit.

The stems dessicate quickly after falling and the eggs will die. It's suprising to see that so many of the cicadas chose such a poor oviposition site. Interestingly, black walnut and hickory leaf stems on our property show no sign of oviposition damage.

description: This appeared to be the waning end of the Great Eastern Brood aka Brood X of the 17-year cicadas. They were still plentiful but the locals said they weren't as thick any more as they had been just a couple of days earlier, so probably past peak in this location. There may have been more than one species in the area based on the songs I heard (or maybe I was just imagining that), but it appeared the predominant one - and all the cicadas I picked up and looked at - were the Magicicada cassinii type with entirely black abdomen. The sound files have some birds mixed in with the cicada chorus. The photos and sound files in this observation were recorded along the edge of the woods with trees on one side of the path and a hay field on the other side. The exuviae and individuals photographed were all crawling on the shrubby vegetation along the forest edge. Also see the following observations that are part of this set: Male - https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/83981587 Female - https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/83981813 Exuviae - https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/83982431 Video footage: https://youtu.be/xxn0UUOlan8

description: We heard Magicicada cassini calls twice when hiking a trail along Farrington Lake that parallels Farrington Lake.  The calls were far enough apart along the trail to be coming from two separate individuals. There was no continuous chorus of cicadas so these appear to be two isolated individuals. We have recorded M. cassini and M. septendecim at other locations, but did not have recording equipment with us today. The first set of calls we heard consisted of a loud pulsing and the second set of calls included the characteristic few seconds of clicking followed by loud pulses of sound. This was not the "wee-oh" of  the Pharaoh cicada, nor was it the sound of annual cicadas. crickets, etc. The pulsing can also be described like a brief "revving" of a chain saw. The clicking was absolutely like what we have heard from Cassini cicadas in other locations.

description: In Bicentennial Park and nearby Louise Drive in East Brunswick, there is a very diffuse emergence of Pharaoh Cicada - their "wee-oh" is faint and coming from "somewhere" in trees above. No individuals have been seen so far and we haven't found any carapaces yet. But they are definitely present in low numbers, generally one singing at a time but there are small clusters where one sings, then another. There are not enough to form a chorus. The song "wee-oh" is very faint on this recording , but I hope you can hear it.  On this recording, you can also hear tennis balls being hit from the nearby tennis court and a chipmunk chirping and bird singing.

This one confuses me. It is a small male, cassinii size. Its ventral abdominal bands are narrow, like Decula, and do not appear to me to go up its sides. I did not discern an orange patch between eye and wing insertion point on its RIGHT SIDE, so I got excited thinking it might be a Decula cicada. But when I looked on its left side (last photo), I see an orange patch, which is indicative of Septendecim, the Pharoah cicada. So I assume this falls within intraspecific variation for Septendecim?  Or can interspecific hybridization occur between Decula and the Pharoah?  Guess it is hard to answer such questions when the adult of the species only emerges every 17 years. Then again, DNA tests could answer the question.  I still have the individual specimen.
